In France, Germany, and also Switzerland, nuclear power plants were shut down or throttled during the July peak because there was too little cooling water available, or the maximum permissible temperature of the return flow was exceeded. There was also damage to roads due to distortions, as well as to railway tracks. Towards the end of the July heatwave, heavy rain in England threatened to break a reservoir, the Toddbrook Reservoir near Manchester. Various storms of the time led to local states of disaster and also claimed some lives – for example:  
in Madrid on August 27;  
in Petingen and Käerjeng during the Luxembourg tornado in August;  
in the Italian Fiumicino at the end of July;  
in Chamoson in Valais in mid-August;  
in Uttendorf and Rußbach at the Gschütt Pass in the state of Salzburg at the beginning and end of July;  
in Obdach, Styria, at the end of August;  
in Katowice, Poland, at the end of July.  
On August 22, lightning strikes around Giewont in the Tatra Mountains claimed several mountain fatalities.
